The outdoor air pollutants that are major factors in human's diseases, causing especially adverse respiratory effects, are particulate matter, sulfur dioxide, nitrogen oxides, volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), while ozone can also affect the respiratory and cardiovascular systems (
 Manisalidis et al., 2020). In addition, climate change resulting from environmental pollution can also affect the geographical distribution of many infectious diseases (
 Akkina et al., 2019; 
 Bezirtzoglou et al., 2011; 
 Linares et al., 2020).
